        <span class="inline-flex items-center gap-1.5 px-3 py-1.5 rounded-lg bg-gray-800 border border-green-500/40 text-sm"><span class="text-white font-bold">LINEN</span><span class="text-green-400 text-xs">5pts</span></span>
      </div>
      <h2 class="text-xl font-light text-blue-400 mt-10 mb-4 border-l-4 border-blue-400 pl-4">Strategy for Textile Words</h2>
      <div class="not-prose my-6 grid grid-cols-1 gap-4">
        <div class="p-4 rounded-xl border border-purple-500/30 bg-purple-950/20 hover:border-purple-400 transition-colors"><p class="text-sm text-gray-300"><span class="text-purple-400 font-semibold">CHINTZ is your best Z play under 7 letters:</span> At 20 points from 6 tiles (3.3 per tile), CHINTZ outscores most Z words. The surrounding letters (C, H, I, N, T) are all common, so you'll often have them when you draw the Z.</p></div>
        <div class="p-4 rounded-xl border border-purple-500/30 bg-purple-950/20 hover:border-purple-400 transition-colors"><p class="text-sm text-gray-300"><span class="text-purple-400 font-semibold">KHAKI uses both K tiles:</span> There's only one K tile in the bag, so KHAKI requires a blank for the second K — or wait until you draw it naturally. But when it works, 16 points from 5 tiles is excellent rack clearance.</p></div>
        <div class="p-4 rounded-xl border border-purple-500/30 bg-purple-950/20 hover:border-purple-400 transition-colors"><p class="text-sm text-gray-300"><span class="text-purple-400 font-semibold">GAUZE for the Z without consonants:</span> If you have the Z but lack consonants, GAUZE (15pts) uses mostly vowels around it. G=2, A=1, U=1, Z=10, E=1 — only one consonant needed.</p></div>
      </div>
      <div class="not-prose my-6 p-5 rounded-xl border border-blue-500/30 bg-blue-950/20">
        <p class="text-sm font-semibold text-blue-400 uppercase tracking-wider mb-2">💡 Key Insight</p>
        <p class="text-base text-gray-200">Textile words are <span class="text-white font-medium">Z and K specialists</span>. CHINTZ, GAUZE, and KHAKI give you reliable plays for two of Scrabble's trickiest high-value tiles. Memorise these three and you'll never be stuck with Z or K on your rack again.</p>
      </div>
